\n|-\n|Grenada||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Kiribati||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|St. Kitts and Nevis||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Libya||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|St. Lucia||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Liechtenstein||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Monaco||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Marshall Islands||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Nauru||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Palau||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Korea, Dem. Rep.||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Solomon Islands||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|San Marino||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Somalia||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|South Sudan||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Seychelles||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Timor-Leste||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Tonga||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Tuvalu||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|St. Vincent and the Grenadines||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|-\n|Samoa||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||||\n|}\nSource: Sachs, J., Schmidt-Traub, G., Kroll, C., Lafortune, G., Fuller, G. (2019): Sustainable Development Report 2019. New York: Bertelsmann Stiftung and Sustainable Development Solutions Network (SDSN).\n\n==Criticisms==\nThe SDGs have been criticized for setting contradictory goals and for trying to do everything first, instead of focusing on the most urgent or fundamental priorities. The SDGs were an outcome from a UN conference that was not criticized by any major [[non-governmental organization]] (NGO). Instead, the SDGs received broad support from many NGOs.<ref>http://www.sustainablesids.org/wp-content/uploads/2018/08/NGOs-leading-SDGs-Sustainable-Brands.pdf</ref>\n\n=== Competing goals ===\n\n{{see also|Food vs. fuel}}\nSome of the goals compete with each other. For example, seeking high levels of quantitative [[GDP growth]] can make it difficult to attain [[ecological]], inequality reduction, and sustainability objectives. Similarly, increasing employment and wages can work against reducing the [[cost of living]].{{citation needed|date=October 2019}}\n\nContinued global economic growth of 3 percent (Goal 8) may not be reconcilable with ecological sustainability goals, because the required rate of absolute global [[eco-economic decoupling]] is far higher than any country has achieved in the past.<ref name=\":15\" /> Anthropologists have suggested that, instead of targeting aggregate GDP growth, the goals could target [[resource]] use per capita, with \"substantial reductions in high\u2010income nations.\"<ref name=\":15\">{{cite journal | last=Hickel | first=Jason | title=The contradiction of the sustainable development goals: Growth versus ecology on a finite planet | journal=Sustainable Development | publisher=Wiley | date=2019-04-15 | issn=0968-0802 | doi=10.1002/sd.1947 | page=}}</ref>\n\n=== Too many goals ===\nA commentary in ''[[The Economist]]'' in 2015 argued that 169 targets for the SDGs is too many, describing them as \"sprawling, misconceived\" and \"a mess\".<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.economist.com/news/leaders/21647286-proposed-sustainable-development-goals-would-be-worse-useless-169-commandments|title=The 169 commandments|newspaper=The Economist|access-date=2016-02-19|issn=0013-0613}}</ref> The goals are said to ignore local context. All other 16 goals might be contingent on achieving SDG 1, ending poverty, which should have been at the top of a very short list of goals. In addition, Bhargava (2019) has emphasized the inter-dependence between the numerous sub-goals and the role played by population growth in developing countries in hampering their operationalization.\n\nOn the other hand, nearly all stakeholders engaged in negotiations to develop the SDGs agreed that the high number of 17 goals was justified because the agenda they address is all-encompassing.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}\n\n=== Weak on environmental sustainability ===\n\nEnvironmental constraints and [[planetary boundaries]] are underrepresented within the SDGs. For instance, the paper \"Making the Sustainable Development Goals Consistent with Sustainability<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Wackernagel|first=Mathis|last2=Hanscom|first2=Laurel|last3=Lin|first3=David|date=2017|title=Making the Sustainable Development Goals Consistent with Sustainability|journal=Frontiers in Energy Research|language=English|volume=5|doi=10.3389/fenrg.2017.00018|issn=2296-598X}}</ref>\" points out that the way the current SDGs are structured leads to a negative correlation between environmental sustainability and SDGs. This means, as the environmental sustainability side of the SDGs is underrepresented, the resource security for all, particularly for lower-income populations, is put at risk. This is not a criticism of the SDGs ''per se'', but a recognition that their environmental conditions are still weak.<ref name=\":15\" />\n\n=== Comparison with Millennium Development Goals ===\nA commentary in ''[[The Economist]]'' in 2015 said that the SDGs are \"a mess\" compared to the eight MDGs used previously.<ref name=\":5\" /> The MDGs were about development while the SDGs are about sustainable development.{{Clarify|reason=What's the difference between \"development\" and \"sustainable development\"?|date=June 2019}} Finally, the MDGs used a sole approach to problems, while the SDGs take into account the inter-connectedness of all the problems.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}}\n\nWhilst the MDGs were strongly criticized by many NGOs as only dealing with the problems, the SDGs deal with the causes of the problems.{{Citation needed|date=October 2017}} Another core feature of the SDGs is their focus on means of implementation, or the mobilization of financial resources, along with capacity building and technology.{{citation needed|date=February 2019}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Action for Climate Empowerment]]\n* [[Economics of climate change mitigation]]\n* [[Education 2030 Agenda]]\n* [[Planetary management]]\n* [[Social Progress Index]]\n* [[Sustainable Development Goals and Iran]]\n\n==Further reading==\nBhargava, A. (2019). \"Climate change, demographic pressures and global sustainability\", ''Economics and Human Biology'', 33, 149\u2013154.\n\nFirzli, Nicolas. \"[https://www.privatedebtinvestor.com/smart-capital-and-sustainable-finance-in-the-sino-american-century/ Smart Capital and Sustainable Finance in the Sino-American Century]\", 16 December 2019, Private Debt Investor\n\nLietaer, Bernard (2019). \"[https://www.sustainable-world.ch Towards a sustainable world - 3 paradigms to achieve]\", available as of Oct.31, 2019 {{ISBN|978-3-200-06527-7}}. Discusses \"the law of sustainability\" presented with Robert E.Ulanowicz and Sally J.Goerner.\n\nWilson, Clive (2018). \"[https://www.routledge.com/Designing-the-Purposeful-World-The-Sustainable-Development-Goals-as-a/Wilson/p/book/9780815381327 Designing the Purposeful World - the Sustainable Development Goals as a blueprint for humanity]\" ''Routledge''\n\nGBS - Associazione nazionale per la ricerca scientifica sul Bilancio Sociale (2019). [https://www.researchgate.net/publication/337334840_THE_SDGs_IN_THE_REPORTS_OF_THE_ITALIAN_COMPANIES_RESEARCH_DOCUMENT_N_16 The SDGs in the reports of the Italian companies]. Authors: \"[https://www.unisalento.it/scheda-utente/-/people/andrea.venturelli Andrea Venturelli]\", Fabio Caputo, Mara Del Baldo, \"[https://www.unimib.it/federica-doni Federica Doni]\", Rossella Leopizzi,\"[https://www.unifg.it/ugov/person/3383 Antonio Corvino]\", \"[https://www.orianaperrone.com Oriana Perrone]\", Mario Minojia, Sara Moggi, Carlo Luison, Gianfranco Rusconi, Lara Tarquinio, Carlo Vermiglio, Gabriele Badalotti, Valeria Fazio, Ruggiero Bodo \", Franco Angeli, 2019, {{ISBN|9788891794901}}.\n\n== Sources ==\n{{Free-content attribution\n| title = Making Sense of MOOCs: A Guide for Policy-Makers in Developing Countries\n| author = Patru, Mariana; Balaji, Venkataraman\n| publisher = UNESCO\n| page numbers = 17-18\n| source = UNESCO\n| documentURL = http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0024/002451/245122E.pdf\n| license statement URL = http://www.unesco.org/ulis/cgi-bin/ulis.pl?catno=245122&set=0058D2750B_1_34&gp=1&lin=1&ll=1\n| license = CC-BY-SA IGO 3.0\n}}\n{{Free-content attribution\n| title = Education for Sustainable Development Goals: Learning Objectives (2017)\n| publisher = UNESCO\n| date = 2017\n| location = Paris\n| page numbers = 7\n| documentURL = http://unesdoc.unesco.org/images/0024/002474/247444e.pdf\n| license statement URL = http://www.unesco.org/ulis/cgi-bin/ulis.pl?catno=247444&set=0058D7C043_2_451&gp=1&lin=1&ll=1\n| license = CC-BY-SA IGO 3.0\n}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|30em|group=\"Note\"}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{offline|med}}\n* [http://sustainabledevelopment.un.org/sdgs UN Sustainable Development Knowledge Platform \u2013 The SDGs]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5_hLuEui6ww Transitioning from the MDGs to the SDGs. Animated video by the United Nations Development Programme (UNDP)]\n* [http://www.project-everyone.org \"Project Everyone\" Campaign] Initial campaign on the SDGs\n* [http://www.globalgoals.org \"Global Goals\" Campaign] Continuing campaign on the SDGs published by Project Everyone\n* [http://www.unwomen.org/en/news/in-focus/women-and-the-sdgs Women and the SDGs (from UNWomen.org)]\n* [https://sdgactioncampaign.org The UN SDG Action Campaign]\n* [http://worldslargestlesson.globalgoals.org/ The World's Largest Lesson (for educators)] with as leading figure [[Nobel prize]] laureate [[Malala Yousafzai]] \n* [https://repositorio.cepal.org/handle/11362/40156 The 2030 Agenda and the Sustainable Development Goals: An opportunity for Latin America and the Caribbean]\n* [http://libraryresources.unog.ch/sdgs Research Guide on the Sustainable Development Goa